WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:53.000
Before we dive into problem framing, we need to establish a shared language — because in this program, words have very specific meanings. 'Innovation' isn't just a buzzword; it's the creation of adopted value. And we're not teaching you to be rogue entrepreneurs — we're teaching you to be intrapreneurs, leading change from within your own hospitals. The three middle terms — systemic friction, root cause versus symptom, and functional flexibility — are the problem-framing vocabulary we'll lean on as we move forward. And the last three definitions here are the psychological engine of this course: you can't innovate using first principles if your team lacks psychological safety, and you won't survive the inevitable setbacks without a growth mindset. Take a moment to review this lexicon — these eight definitions are the guardrails for the rest of the program.
